{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_india_ver02/data/sn83045433/100493329/1907122901/0804.xml":{"full_text":"WILD MAN IS CAUGHT\nyah\nRoamed in Belgian Forests\nfor Twelve Years.\nnjght in Masonic Tem\nh\nA\ndeputy grand master, Henry Simpson;\nIS A SHIPWRECKED SAILOR\nJunior\nOnly Survivor of the Norwegian\nBarque Mygrean Resembled an\nAnimal, and Fought His Captors.\nMental Activity Restored When\nAddressed in Native Tongue.\n\n\n\n\n\nBrussels, Dec. 28.\u2014A lone survivor of\nthe wreck of the Norwegian bark My\nsrean, wrecked on the French coast In\n18%, has just been found in the forest\nof Soignles, near the Belgian town of\nthe same name.\nNew York, Dec. 26.\u2014A Universa\na in May. 1906\nConvention, signed in Rome in May, 136,\n2 i\nf\u00a5 contained a provision which went into]\non the first of last October, for\n\u201cInternational reply coupons\u201d to be\nissued and redeemed by all the countries progosed\ny\nCrazed by the terrors of the wreck, the\ndreadful battle in the waves after his\nship went down, and the violence with\nwhich he was battered on the rocks to\nwhich he finally clambered from the sea,\nthe sallor has wandered for twelve years,\na veritable wild man, in thickly settled\nFrance and Belgium.\nsubse to the convention.\n\n\n\n\n4\nd\nHis mysterious appearance from time\nto time in the outskirts of Soignies finally\nled to the organization of a party to\nhunt him down. Those who saw him\ndescribed him as a monstrous ape-like\ncreature who swung himself from tree\nto tree, but always vanished when any\none was bold enough to address him,\n\n\n\n\n\nEE\n\n\n\n\nThe hunters hid in a thicket where he\nhad been seen and were rewarded by a\nglimpse of him after several hours\u2019 wait\ning. He fled when the party tried to\nseize him, and was pursued to a near-by\nvillage, where he was cornered and over\npowered.\ni\nrete\ni\nw\nE\u2014\u2014\n\nSik X\nLooked Like an Animal,\n\nIn appearance he was scarcely human.\nHis hair was long and matted, his body\nalmost naked, and his skin weatherbeaten\nand scarred until he was as black as a\nnegro. Around his neck was a chain, with\na meda] attached, on which was the werd\n\u201cMygrean.\u201d\n\ni\n\n\n\nw\u2014\u2014\u2014\n\n1\n\n\nInvestigation revealed the fact that a\nvessel of that name had been lost off the\nFrench coast, and the Norwegian philan\nthropist, Baron Grynsdaal, hearing of the\ncase, sent funds to have the castaway\nsent back to Norway.\n\n\n\n\nHis identity was dramatically revealed,\nWhile a captive in Belgium, no one was\nable to induce him to speak. On going\naboard the Norwegian ship at Antwerp,\nhowever, he was suddenly adaressed by\nthe captain in Norweglan, gave a terrified\ncry, and fell in a fit.\n\n\ntuat rks were first used in 480\nSeahoer must ify by examina\nJ gland TaLzat for the promotion of\nWhen he recovered he was able to an\nswer the captain's geestions intelligibly,\nsaid his name was Jensen, and that he\nwas, indeed, one of the crew of the My\ngrean, He lost consciousness, he added,\nwhile trying to reach shore after the\nMygrean broke up, and of his subsequent\nwanderings in the French and Belgian\nforests had but the vaguest recollection.\nER oe oe\nA Spa ghter sometimes gets $2000 for a\nBr a a\nIt costs over $1.00 fire a single shot from one\nee I a of el 1 the Trench samy.\n's of a iq om change as it develons\nio. dinailh but aft iddie us I\nrrow Iaroos pe\nges\nOver 0 per t of the natives of India till the\nland w 3 m is scattered. and\nHUGHES TO HAVE MANAGER.\nMai. DEI 5 wi\nGovernor Feels His Candidavy Is\nBeing Poorly Handled\nCor 0 detailed it al jepa\u2019tment. tem orary\njuty New York Cit ns\n3 4 Besigution 2 Se Tm Lie CHESTER H al\nNew York, Dec. 28.\u2014Believing there has\nbeen too much blundering by well-wishing\nbut ill-advised admirers of Gov. Hughes,\nfriends of the New York executive, it is\nreported in political circies, will inaugu\nrate a movement within a week or ten\ndays to place his candidacy in the hands\nof men thoroughly familiar with practical\npolitics and push an aggressive campaign.\nH L iEIX Twelfth Infant tccepted\ni 6 Capt. EDWARD A. KREGER, a ge ad\nJ a on a a n 3 IR BREED: Sim #35 sitesiod in a. Paria\nprovisional government of (ad afe the other for insulting two Englishmen. In\nA Post CONNOLLY expland\u00e9tion vid 1 annot help it: whenever I\nity ong Pe pci 0\u00b0 amuaged thar 1\n~p m\ni Geperal Staff, direct A refi architecture\nFa Ebon g\nuy reget J 3\ng Jefferson. Street Baptist (hrech\n2 wa ir f brick, even e apex\nrick being especia ashioned for the place it\nIt !s understood they will not act with\nout a thorough understanding with the\ngovernor, although this does not mean\nthat he is to become an active candidate.\nThe names of former Mayor Seth Low and\nE. R. L. Gould are mentioned as possible\nleaders of his campaign.\nme\nPie r ta s abo three mes as\nR NOOON r Italian Drovine war\nBY g 3 3 ia and\nsilkvon ef vs we i pk\na| SE pounds, With 2 value of\n6 SR\n\nand\nHughes is to make a Washington's\nBirthday address before the Union\nLeague Club in Chicago, and it is ex\npected he will then make a definite an\nnouncement of his position on national\nquestions.\ni at t\nb expe\ni Ai: wei pa\narise wifessed the faith 3 Te\neS i\nthe lariont He forth De\ne of Muss e\n\nMr. Calderhead\u2019's Illness\n\nRepresentative Calderhead, of Kansas,\nwho is seriously ill at his apartments in\nCongress Hall, was reported yesterday\nas slightly improved, but not out of\ndanger. His physicians are hopeful of his\nrecovery. The patient's family has been\n\n\n\n\n\n\nts\nnotified, but up to a late hour last night\nnot arrived\nR\nNervous, Weak,\nRun-Down Women\n\nThousands of Women, Who Suffered\nFor Years, Have Been Restored\nTo Complete Health by\nStuart\u2019s Calcium Wafers.\ndew 8S rom st\ni\n\n\n\n\n\nv\nTrial Package Free.\n\nto Hospital, ng racks. for\nAre you nervous, weak, tired, run-down,\ndispirited, easily exhausted\u2014in other\nwords, do you feel like a dishrag at\ntimes? Do you ever have to stop right in\nthe middle of your work to take a rest?\n4 duty with Comvany C, H\n\n\n\n\nNearly every woman has these misera\nble experiences, and many such sufferers\nseek relief in secret remedies, containing\nharmful drugs and cheap alcohol. If you\nare doing this stop it now, before you\nruin your health completely. Your con\ndition is bad enough without making it\nworse.\n\n\nESI\n\n\n\n\n\nee Le\nYou need a tonic that will brace up the\nnervous system, cleanse the bowels, liver,\nand kidneys, and enrich the blood. The\nbest, purest, safest preparation to do this\nis Stuart's Calcium Wafers.\nEi\nJ\n\nl\nee\nStuart's Calclum Wafers are not a se\ncret remedy. They do not contain harm\nful drugs, nor do they lose their medicinal\npower as most liquid medicines do, be\ncause these wafers are in tablet or\nlozenge form, which cannot deteriorate or\nevaporate.\ncr Hans fy ore; Paduwah. and Bu\nDes Moines, Scorpion, Prairie. Tacoma Dubuque,\nPaducah Marietta detached Atlantic Fleet\nand assigne service\neS\n\n\nStuart\u2019s Calcium Wafers contain sul\nphide of calcium, the strongest blood\npurifier known; also golden seal, quassia,\neucalyptus, belladonna, and the vegetable\nalteratives and laxatives. These Ingredi\nents will restore the normal action of the\nbowels, liver, and kidneys: invigorate the\nnerves and brain; make pure, rich, healthy\nblood; drive away that tired, worn-out\nfeeling and make you feel ten years\nyounger.\nes\n\nf\n\ni\n\nYou can obtain Stuart's Calcium Wafers\nin any drug store at only fifty cents a box.\n*but If you have any doubts as to the\nmerits of these wonderful calcium wafers,\nwhy, send us your name and address and\nwe will send you a free sample package,\n80 you can give them a fair trial and\nSonyince Sourucit. Write to-day. Address\n175\nBldg.\nJEFFERSON AND ADAMS.\n\u201cBy degrees Jeflerson became\na poor man, and, indeed, worse\nthan poor, since he wax in\nvolved in pecuniary embarrass\nments. Before matters had\nreached this stage he had sold\nhis library to Congress for\nR23,050.\n&0, Free and Accepted Ma\nsenior grand warden, George C. Ober:\n\n\u201cAlthough he expressed him\nself as desiring nothing from\nthe publie Treasury, he accepted\npecuniary aid, furnished by pri\nvate subscription, with the pa\nthetic statement:\nIE\n\n\u201clI have speni three times as\nmuch money, and given my\nwhele life to my countrymen,\nand now they nobly come for\nward in the only way they ean\nand save an old servant from\nbeing turned, like a dog, out of\ndoors.\u2019\n\nUni 1 Pe ta]\n\u201cJohn Quincey Adams, a short\ntime before he retired from the\nPresidency, and in cbmpletion of\nthat event, wrote as follows:\n\u201c\u201cThe income of my whole\nprivate estate in less than $6,000\na year, and I am paying at least\n\u00a32,000 of that for interest on my\ndebt. Finally, upon going out\nof office in one year from this\ntime, destitute of all means of\nacquiring property, it will only\nbe by the sacrifice of that which\nI now possess that I shall be\nable to support my family.\nGrover Cleveland.\nCLEVELAND FEELS\nNATION'S NEGLECT\nContinued from Page One,\nest pinnacle of honor, and yet decrees that\nas ex-President he is but a melancholy\nproduct,\u201d doomed to unescapably sad con\nditions? Is their enther comfort nor honor\nin his release from exhausting Presiden\ntial labor and perplexity, in the respect\nand esteem accorded to him by his fel\nlow-citizens, on every side, and the neigh\ndorly welcome that greets him on his\nreturn to the fellowship of private sta\ntion?\ni\n\n\u201cThe truth is, that our people, so far\nfrom treating their ex-Presidents simply\nas relics of past honors, seem disposed\nnot only to bestow on them honor and\nrespect, but to continue them in service\nso far as to interfere seriously with their\nuntrammeled return to private cltizen\nship. and their unrestrained resumption\nof the occupations of everyday life.\n\nFeeling of Public.\n\u201cThere is a sort of vague, but none the\nless imperative, feeling abroad in the\nland that one who has occupied the great\noffice of President holds in trust for his\nfellow-citizens a certain dignity which,\nin his conduct and manner of life, he js\nbound to protect against loss or deterio\nration.\n\u201cObedience to this obligation. which can\nhardly be avoided, limits the ex-President\nin his choice of an occupation and means\nof livelihood, and prescribes for him only\nsuch work as in popular judgment is not\nundignified, and it also enforces a scala\nof living on his part frequently less in\nkeeping with his financial ability than\nwith popular conceptions of exPresiden\ntial propriety.\u201d\ny le\nOf an ex-President's occupation, Mr.\nCleveland writes: \u201cBut it is not the re\nstraints to which he is subjected, as a\nmere depositary of the people's dignity,\nwhich remind him most directly that his\nretirement means something very differ\nent from an absolute rest and freedom\nfrom the people's service.\nHas Many Offers,\n\u201cHe Is deluged with newly written\nbooks\u2014most of them indifferent or posi\ntively worthless\u2014and these he is ex\npected to read and commend for adver\ntising purposes, He is made a target for\nall manner of pecuniary solicitation, em\nbracing all sorts of objects, ranging from\nlarge endowment funds and disinterested\noffers of fabulously profitable invest\nment, to pathetic and aepressing appeals\nfor the relief of individual \u2018distress.\n\n\n\u201cHe Is almost daily importuned to join\nin the management of public or semi\npublic enterprises, which profess to be\nuseful, or beneficent, or charitable, He\nis persistently urged to make addresses\non topics, and for purposes, that are be\nwildering, and at times and places that\nare Impossible. His daily mail furnishes\nconclusive evidence that his existence is\nnot overlooked by any class or condition\nof our people, in any corner of our land,\nand the visitors he receives forbid the\nreflection that he is only a \u2018melancholy\nproduct\u2019 of our governmental system\n\n\n\nGams Oo\nDENIES SIGNING DEEDS.\nRR GREY i\nWoman Who Was Practically a Pris\noner Complains of Treaiment.\nChicago, Dec. 28.\u2014Miss Annie M. Nolan,\naged and wealthy spinster, recovered\nsuciently this afternoon from the stupor\nin which she has lain since she was res\ncued by the police from the rooming\nhouse conducted by Mrs. Ruth Laughlin,\nto declare that if she signed deeds giv\ning her $10,000 property to Mrs, Laughlin\n\n\n\n\n\nshe did it unconsciously.\nMrs. Laughlin; A, 8. Kelly, a broker,\nand Moses D, Brown, an attorney, were\narrested this afternoon and remanded in\nlieu of $1,000 bonds. The police charge\nthem with conspiracy to gain the wealth\nof the spinster, and will attempt to\nprove that they kept her a prisoner,\nstupefied with alcohol, until her strength\nwas so wasted that there is doubt of her\nrecovery.\n\n\n\n\n\nstn\n0.\nopp. Treasury.\nra \u2014\u2014\u2014eer i.\nate may be\nFuneral of Mrs Stenhens\nClu a oun a\nThe funeral of Mrs. Caroline M. Ste\nphens, who died Friday night, will be\nheld to-morrow afternoon at 2 o'clock at\nher late home, 417 B Street northeast.\nInterment will be in Glenwood Cemetery.\nRev. Dr. France, pastor of Trinity Metho\ndist Church, will conduct the servicac\nAn escort of twenty-four policemen,\nheaded by Capt. Daley, Lieut. Falvey,\nand two sergeants from the Ninth police\nprecinct, conducted the remains of the\nlate Policeman Philip Mansfield, of the\nNinth precinct, to his last resting place,\nCongressional Cemetery, vesterday after\nnoon. Funeral services were held at the\nhome, 1210 Eleventh street southeast\nI HH -__ ___ TN\nSALE AT G. ERLEBACHER\u2019S.\nWomen of Taste Are Offered Bar.\nRains at New F Streed Stama\nWomen of taste find much to interest\nthem at G. Erlebacher's, the new women's\nstore, 1222 F street northwest.\nThis firm has in a short time sprung\ninto the front rank of Washington's busi\nness world and enjoys a representative\nclientele which is growing. Only the bet\nter class of goods is shown by this house.\nSpecial attention is called to an elab\norate exhibit of the newest and smartest\ndomestic and Parisian creations in\nwomen's sults and coats, and to furs and\nevening waists.\nTo-morrow this firm will inaugurate its\nfirst sale. Big price reductions have been\nmade,\n\nBurial of Police ares\nCALLS HARAHAN LIAR\nMaxwell Edgar Says Fish Is\nin Lead with Proxies.\nANSWERS RECENT INTERVIEW\nDeclares Illinois Central Head's\nClaim of Control Is Childish and\nCount Was Stopped at Letter \u201cT\u201d in\nOrder that Road\u2019s President Might\nNot Be Convicted of Perjury.\nChicago, Dec. 28.\u2014\"\u201cStuyvesant Fish\n\u2018hoids many more proxies to-day than he\n\u2018had at the October meeting, and, judging\nfrom the receipts, of new proxies and\nrevocations, he should have a clear ma\njority over all on March 2.\u201d\nThis assertion was made in a statement\ngiven out by Maxwell Edgar, for the Fish\ninterests to-day, in answer to a recent\ninterview of President J. T. Harahan, of\n\u2018the Illinois Central Railroad.\nhan\nBB\n\u201cIn his interview Mr. Harahan starts\nout by claiming that nearly 80 per cent of\nthe Chicago stockholders have given thelr\nproxies to him,\u201d said Mr. Edgar. \u201cThere\nare some 50,000 shares owned in Chicago,\nnot more than 40,000 of which will prob\nably be voted. On Mr, Harahan's state\nment, this would give only 8,000 shares to\nMr. Fish and 3,000 shares to Mr. Hara\nhan,\nHis Veracity Questioned,\n\u201cUnfortunately for Mr. Harahan's ve\nracity or lack of it, there are ten large\nstockholders in Chicago who among them\nhave given Mr. Fish more than 8,00\nvotes, including the biggest individual\nblock in Chicago of 3,500, for which Mr.\nFish holds the proxy. If Mr. Fish, with\nten stockholders out of about 4% Chicago\nstockholders, holds proxies for over 8,00\nshares, how can Mr. Harahan hold 80\nper cent?\n\n\u201cThis \u00a2hlidish claim of Mr. Harahan\nis on a par with his false and reckless af\nfidavit of October 15, in which he stated\nunder oath that he and those with him\nwould cast at the October election the\nvotes of mere than 59.000 shares.\nCount Stopped ap \u201cT.\"\n\u201cIf this statement had been true he\nwould have controlled over and above\nthe enjoined stock more votes than Mr.\nFish, When the votes were counted as\nfar as the letter \u201cTT it was found that\nMr. Fish was very many thousands in\nthe lead, and the count was then dropped,\nin order that Mr. Harahan might not\nbe convicted of perjury.\u201d\n\nSHAW APPEALS FOR HARMONY\nCombats Idea That New York or\nOhio Will Furnish Candidate.\nSays Individuality, Not Geography,\nWill Dictate Convention's Choice,\nand Scouts a Walkover,\nDes Moines, Jowa, Dec. 28. \u2014Senator\nLeslie M. Shaw i= headed for Iowa, and\nwill address Des Moines bankers next\nweek on currency reform. Incidentally, he\nwill iook into the political situation to see\nwhat encouragement might develop in be\nhalf of a Shaw Presidential boom.\nAnticipatory of his visit, Secretary\nShaw wrote the Des Moines Capital a\nletter, which was published this evening,\nand is causing a vast amount of com\nment.\nThe Capital stated a few days ago that\nVhio or New York was almost certain to\nfurnish the next Republican candidate.\nShaw's letter combats this theory, and\ndeclares that individuality, and not geo\ngraphical location, will @etermine the\nconvention's cholce.\n\u201cFrom Lincoln to Roosevelt,\u201d he ob\nserved, \u201cit was the man and not the\nlecation which determined results, and\nCleveland was even nominated against\nthe wishes of an opposing delegation from\nhis own State.\u201d\nThat Secretary Shaw feels this is the\ntime to end the factional war in lowa is\nevidenced by a warning that \u201cwe are not\nlikely to have a walkover in 1%8\" and\nthat \u201cthis is not the time for dissensions\nwithin the party ranks.\u201d He concludes:\n\u201cThe next Republican nationai convention\nis likely to present a more interesting\ncontest than has been witnessed for\nyears.\n\u201cLet us hope that before it adjourns it\nwill select that man who best represents\nthe principles of the party and the one\nwho will be most loyal to these principles\nafter the election, and whose administra\ntion will best conserve the interests of\n90,000,000 people, regardless of the State\nof his birth or State of his choice,\u201d\nMr. Shaw's appeal for harmony is in\nterpreted here as also reflecting the belief\nthat so long as factional! war is to con\ntinue neither Cummins nor himself can\nhope for further prestige in national po\nlitical affairs.\nNO appearance by Mrs. Fiske in the\nrecent years, during which her successive\noriginations have added tc the modern\ndrama series of characters representing\nand illustrating a versatild and unique\ndramatic genius, has attracted wider at\ntention or inspired a more_ legitimate cu\nriosity than now attach to her forthcom\ning assumption of the role. of Rebecca\nWest, in Ibsen's great drama, \u201cRosmers\nholm.\u201d Although this play has been seen\nIn various European cities, its chief actor\nabroad being Eleanora Duse, this will be\nits first adequate representation in Eng\nlish. Bringing to all the characters the\nlllustration of which she undertakes that\nanalysis which has made her impersona\nHons famous, Mrs. Fiske has had the roie\nof Rebecca West in study for several\nyears, and her past achievements promise\nan interpretation of this fascinating and\ndifficult character in line with the best\nof her work and illuminative in a high\ndegree. One cannot read thie remarkable\nplay without a wish for its representation\non the stage in the best possible cireum\nstances; and that such a representation\nwill now be made, seems clear, for be\nyond the promise of Mrs. Fiske, in the\nchief role, there is assurance of a pro\nduction by Harrison Grey Fiske, that will\nbe faithful as to scenic environment, while\nthe various strong and individual char\nacters in \u201cRosmersholm,\u201d aside from Re-\nbecca West, will have the best available\nactors as interpreters. There is no other\nplay of Ibsen's, in which the requirements\nof varied ability in the acting are greater,\nand Bruce McRae, George Arliss, Albert\nBruning, Fuller Meilish, and Florence\nMontgomery, associated with Mrs. Fiske\nin this production, give assurance of a\nrealization of full character values. \u201cRos\nmersholm\u2122 is a play of intense interest,\nand as notably as any other of Ibsen's\nworks, Is describes this great author's\nunapproached skill in dramatic situation\nand Mrs. Fiske will play an en\ngagement limited to three weeks at the\nLyric Theater, New York, and at its con\nclusion will make a tour of the principal\n\n4\nTHE WASHINGTON HERALD, SUNDAY, DECEMBER 29, 1907.\nCa fn 12 WY i x ner iF a a $i Aa L 0) 3 5 Tr EE x GN of EAE 0 hes ol oy Sal gl hs\nRio Bie aii pa ok RE, ER an Pv Cale oh SA Re SF oo PEA Fo A, 3 X\nko i 5% rt A oy Bi Sn es SE FR SR 4 Ses a RICE 3 ths Bab X 5\n3 i Zi\n11\nMrs. Fiske nnd Ihsan\nLAURA M. CARTER SUES.\nWants 87,950 for Aiding in Capture\nof Forging Bank Teller.\n\nNew York, Dec. 28.\u2014Laura M. Carter\nhas begun suit against the Windsor Trust\nCompany for $7,950, claimed as due her in\na reward for surrendering the forging\nteller, Chester B, Runyan, to the police.\nThe company hag answered with the\nsuit for $25,000, charging her with being\nin a conspiracy with Runyan to rob the\ninstitution, and asserting that she re\nceived that amount of the money. Run\nyan stole $96,000 from the company, dis\nappeared, spent several days in the\nwoman's company, and was given up by\nher.\nMrs. Carter was also argested and\ntried, but\u2018was acquitted on the criminal\ncharge\nEMPLOYES ATTEND RITES.\nFaneral of Joseph W. Bartlett Con\nducted Yesterday.\nFuneral services over the body of\nJoseph W. Bartlett, who died suddenly\nof heart failure Wednesday morning last,\nwere held at 11 o'clock yesterday morning\nat the home, 324 Maryland avenue north\neast. Rev. W, IL, Devrice, of St. Mark's\nEpiscopal Church, officiated. Interment\nwas in the Glenwood Cemetery.\nThe pallbearers were Gen. A. C. Park\ninson, 8, B. Platt, Clarence Johnson,\nC. N. Richards, George H. Boyd. and\nPaul Draper. Ail employes of the Senate\nsecretary's office atiended the services,\nand placed a floral offering upon the bier,\nMr. Bartlett was seventy-one years of\nage, and came to this city to be a tally\nclerk of the House of Representatives\nabout thirty years ago.\nWHEELING FACTORIES T0 OPEN\nAbout 15,000 Men Will Return to\nWork Next Week.\nSheet Steel Mills and Poiteries Are\nReady to Start\u2014Several Glass\nFactories Also Need Men.\nWheeling, W. Va,, Dec. 38.\u2014The indus\ntrial depression which has affected some\nthing like 15,900 men in Wheeling and the\nadjacent Ohio Valley, due entirely to the\nstringency in the money market, has ap\nparently been lifted, for orders were re\nceived two-day to put the greater number\nof idle men to work on January 2.\nIn Wheeling at least 4,000 men, who\nhave been idle most of the time for two\nmonths, will get started on Monday, and\nin adjacent manufacturing establishments\nseven te eight thousand men are ordered\nto work either Monday or Thursday\nmornings.\nThe return of prosperity applies to all\nclasses of workers. The American Sheet\nand Tin Plate Company, a subsidiary of\nthe United States Steel Company, has\nordered 2.500 men at their Laughlin tin\nplate plant on Monday morning; their\nlabel plant, with 200, will resume work\nin a week, and the Aetna Standard sh: ot\nmill, employing 2,3% men, will start half\nits mills Monday and the other nalf in a\nweek.\nThe Wheeling Potteries Company, the\nRiverside Pottery, and the Warwick Pot\ntery, all of Wheeling, employing over\n150 men, have orders to start January 2.\nThe Wheeling Corrugating Company,\nemploying 5X men, will start half its\nmen January-2, and 40 men of the La\nBell Iron Company's 1,600 in this oF are\nordered to work Monday.\nThe Wheeling Canning Company.\nploying 3% men, after being idle three\nmonths, will start in full force Monday;\nthe Novelty Stamping Company, of Bel\nlaire, and the Wheeling Enameling\nWorks, at Elm Grove, employing 10\nmen, will start Monday after six weeks\u2019\nidleness. The Northwood Glass Com\npany, 3X men, will resume the first of\nthe year.\nGrand Opera Coming\nOn the night of Monday, January 13,\na grand opera festival will be\ninadgurated at the Belasco Thea\nter with the performance of \u201cLa\nGiaconda,\u201d by the San Carlo Grand\nOpera Company. Mr. Henry Russell, the\ndirector of the San Cario Grand Opera\nCompany, is touring the country with 175\nartists, among whom most of them are\nfamous on both continents. His list of\nprincipal singers is equal te that of any\nof the grand opera companies now in\nthis country. This company includes\nFlorencio Constantino, the great Spanish\ntenor, whe captivated American music\nlovers last season when the San Carlo\nGrand Opera Company made its first tour\nin the United States. Alice Nielsen, that\nfamous young American grand opera so\nprano, whose Rosina in the \u201cBarber of\nSeville,\u201d won for her the most enthu\nsiastic praise throughout the tour to the\nPacific Coast and back. De Segurola,\nwhose Escamille in \u201cCarmen,\u201d and Me\nphistopheles in \u201cFaust\u201d are world famous.\nMr. Russell has engaged Mme. Jane\nNoris, dramatic sopranc of the Grand\nOpera, of Paris; Tino de Sana, lyric so\nprano, of La Scala; Mlle. Rosa Olitzka,\nthe great Polish mezzo soprano: Maria\nClaessens, contralto, of La Scala; Milan,\nGuglielmina Marchi, mezzo soprano; L.\nd\u2019Aubigne, the famous tenor, who was\nborn in this county; Mlle. Bramonia and\nAnnita Perego, soprano; Carlo Dani, Er\nnesto Glaccone, and Guiseppi Oppezzo,\ntenors; Victor Maurel, the famous actor\nsinger of remarkable personality; Ramon\nBlanchart, Rodolfo Fornari, Adamo Gal\nperin, Attilio Pulcini, barytones, and\nGuillo Rossi, and Linge Tavecchia,\nbassos. One of the best-known conduc\ntors of Italy, Signor Arnaldo Conti, is\nin charge of the orchestra of sixty-two\nmusicians.\n\nThe following repertoire will be given\nin Washington by the San Carlo Grand\nOpera Company: \u201cLa Gioconda\u201d (in\nItalian); Faust (in French); Rigoletto (in\nItalian); \u201cLohrengrin\u201d (in German);\n\u201cCavalleria,\u201d Rusticana,\u201d \u201cI'Pagliacel,\u201d\nand \u201cLucia\u201d (In Italian).\nHissed His Own Piav\nNicholas Pradon, the French dramat\u2019zt,\nwith a well-founded idea that nothi Ig\narouses applause at a theater so much\nas any demonstration that has the ap\npearance of spite or malice against the\nplay or the players, bethough him that\nhe would enlist the sympathy of the au\ndience by going in front and hissing his\nown play. He carried out this plan with\nsuch apparent vindictiveness that he fair\nly provoked the indignant anger of a\nneighbor, who offered some severe re\nmonstrances upon the impropriety of his\nconduct. Pradon, delighted with the suc\ncess of his maneuvers, obstinately per\nsevered in them until his expostulator,\ndriven out of all endurance, turned upon\nhim and belabored him soundly, thus sat\nisfying the dramatist that his popularity\nwas too secure to be affected by the spite\nof any cabal. The author at last got\nout of the hands of his.own champion,\nand left the theater contused but con\ntent.\nStenographers in Ression\nNew York, Dec. 28.\u2014The New York\nState Stenographers\u2019 Association conclud\ned its thirty-second annual convention\nto-night with a dinner at the Hotel Man\nhattan, at which about seventy were\npresent. Henry C. Deming, State geol\nogist of Pennsylvania, and Theodore F.\nthe house than any lyceum orator could drag in\nwith bands a-playing.\nMa says that if some men would confine their\ncranking to their autos, the lives of some women\nwould be a jolly romp.\nMen believe in heredity, 'cause when\nShuey. stenographer of the United States\nSenate, were guests.\nthe smart things their children say the inference is\nthat they are responsible,\nAID TO MAIL SERVICE\nNew Postal Coupon to Help\nForeign Correspondents.\nCOVERS THE RETURN POSTAGE\nSlip May Be Purchased in One Coun\ntry, Malled to a Person in Another,\nan! Exchanged for a Stamp of\nFive-cent Value\u2014Have Not Come\nInto General Use as Yet,\nThis coupon may be bought in any\npost-office of any such country, and sent\nby the purchaser to a correspondent in\nany other country, where the post-office\nwill redgem it with the equivalent of a\nfive-cent stamp. which prepays the post\nage on the correspondent\u2019s answering let\nter,\nOne of these reply coupons has the ap\npearance of a small piece of paper money,\nbeing printed on thin, white paper in\nblue ink over a background of clouds\nand vines in olive green. The size of the\ncoupon is 4 by 3% inches.\nOn the top border of the face, in rather\nheavy capital letters, are the words:\n\u201cCoupon-response international.\u201d and be\nneath, in small letters, the English\nequivalent, \u201cInternational reply coupon.\u201d\nBeneath this line, just above the main\ndesign, is the instrpetion, printed in\nEnglish and repeated in French below\nthe sign, \u201cThis coupon can be exchanged\nfor a postage stamp of the value of 25\ncentimes (2%d.), or the equivalent of\nthat sum in countries which have adopted\nthe arrangement.\u201d The back of the\ncoupon bears this same sentence, printed\nin German, Spanish, Italian, French, and\nEfglish.\nThe principal design on the face of the\ncoupon is the figure of a flying woman\nin a loose robe and scarf, her right hand\nlightly touching a globe representing the\nEastern hemisphere, Her left hand holds\na letter, which she is offering to the.\nWestern hemisphere.\nIn Several Languages.\nNear the lower border of the face ap\npears the name of the country of issue in\nFrench and the language of the country\nof issue, the English issue reading \u201cGrand\nBretagne\u2014Great Britain.\u201d In the process\nof their service the coupons are further.\nmarked, the left hand, or Eastern hemi\nsphere, being postmarked by the office of\nissue, the other being postmarked by the\noffice which redeems the coupon by giv\ning a \u201cresponse\u2019 stamp in exchange\nfor it.\nThe convention which provided for these\ncoupons superceded the Washington Uni\nversal Postal Convention signed in June,\n1897, and the Rome convention included,\nso far as the United States are con-|\ncerned, nearly every country in the world\nhaving a post-office, with the exceptions\nof Canada, Mexico, Cuba, and the Repub\nlic of Panama, with which countries we\nhave separate postal conventions.\nSo If you have a correspondent\nwish to supply a reply coupon to in Zulu\nland, Sarawak, or Chile, you inclose him\nonk, he exchanges it for a stamp of his\u2019\ncountry which equals in value one of our\nS-cent stamps, and neither of you have\nmore to do in respect to the transaction,\nBut the troubles of the two post-offices\ninvoived have only begun. These post\noffices treat the coupons as if they were\nchecks, and they must be put through\nclearing-house process universal in pore\nNot Popular Here,\nE. P. Russell, cashier of the New York\npost-office, sald to-day that the reply cou\npons had not yet become popular here,\nprobably because the city\u2019s foreign colony\nwas not yet acquainted with them. They\nare \u201ccleared\u201d quarterly, and the first\nquarte- of their use has not quite ended,\nso the cashier's figures respecting them\nwere not made up. But, speaking from\ngeneral knowledge, Mr. Russell said he\nthought that not more thap 10.60 of the\ncoupons had been issued in this city.\nThe first patrons of the office to under-\nstand the convenience of the coupons\nwere merchants with correspondents in\nsmall distant seaports, to whom they Se\nthe coupons by hundreds.\nFor his trouble in handling the coupons,\nUncle Sam gets a cent for each, the sell-\ning price being six cents. All purchasers\nare warned to instruc: those to whom\ncoupons are gent that th: coupons are not\nthemselves valid for postage, but must be\nexchanged for postage sStamns\nBENNETT MAY ROW ABROAD.\nSculler from Springfield, Mass, as\nCandidate for Olymple Regatta,\nNew York, Dec. 2X -Many oarsmen\nthroughout the United States have picked\nout Harry S. Bennett as the one best fit\nted to carry the country\u2019s colors in the\nsingle sculls event at the Olympic Row\ning Championships, to be decided in Eng\nland mext season. Bennett, who comes\nfrom Springfield, Mass, is the amateur\nchampion sculler of the United States.\nHe is in prime condition now, and ready\nto start training the moment his entry is\naccepted.\nThat the Englishmen fear this self\nmade sculler is borne out by the fact that\nthey have resurrected H. T. Blackssaffe,\nthe veteran runner-up for Ned Ten Eyck,\nand winner of the diamond sculls in 196.\nAlfred Shrubb Wins Race.\nBoston, Dec. 28.\u2014Plodding mile after\nmile, Alfred Shrubb, the king of the long\ndistance runners, proved conclusively that\nhe is unbeatable, by winning from three\nof the best professional runners in Amer\njca to-night at the Park Square rink in\nthe ten-mile relay race against Williams,\nMeyvers, and Kanaly, by six laps.\nSIS HOPKINS\u2019 SAYINGS.\nBY ROSE ELVILLE.\nIt is hard to be high-mirded and live in a flat.\nle driving man is ofton unbridled in his be\nhavior,\nA fashionable woman is like an auto. She is wel\nattized.\nif you want to be kind to your friends, don\u2019t visit\nthem.\nNear-sighted men seem scarce around the Flat\nBuilding.\nIt is sometimes harder to get by than up to the\nbargain counter.\nMa says a clever man i8 usually bandy at giving\naway other people's money,\nA good many people who do their duty as they\nsee it should visit am oculist.\nMa's motto for framing: Nobody cares for the\nman who doesn\u2019t care for somebody.\nPa says some people put their savings under their\npillow at night, to prove that they have momey to\nretire on.\nThe ome trouble about being high-tone\u00a2 *s that\nwhen you get your picture im the paper sou are\nMa says curtain lectures drive more men out of\nMASONS NAME OFFICERS.\nMr. Augustus B. Coolidge Elected\nGrand Master.\nple and elected officers for the coming\nyear, as follows:\nGrand master, Augustus B. Coolidge;\nd warden, J. Claude_Keiper:\ngrand secretary, Arvine W. Johnston:\ngrand treasurer, Past Grand Master\nJames A. Sample; grand Yecturer, Thomas\nH. Young; grand chaplain, Joseph Daw\nson; assistant grand chaplain, J. Russell\nVerbrycke; grand marshal, Benjamin W.\nMurch; senior grand deacon, Charles Er\nBaldwin; junior grand deacon, T. John\nNewton; grand sword bearer, Alexander\nGrant; grand pursuivant, W. W. Jer\nmane; senior grand steward, J. W. Wit\nten, junior grand steward, Lew Towers,\nJr.; grand tiler, Warren C. Bickford.\nAlbert F. Fox was elected trustee for\nthree years; James A. Sample, representa\ntive in Masonic Temple Association:\nFrancis J. Woodman, corporator in Ma\nsonic Hall Association; representatives on\nboard of directors of Masonic and Eastern\nStar Heme, Lurtin R. Ginn, Charles J.\nJames, L. Cabell Williamson.\nRUSSIA RAIDS NEWSPAPERS.\nOfficers Arrest 100 Employes, Scent\ning Bomb Plot.\nSt. Petersburg, Dec. 2X. \u2014In unearthing\nanother revolutionary conspiracy, the po\nlice to-day rounded up the newspaper of\nfices of the Soveremnoye Slivo and Se\ngodyna, and arrested 10 members of the\nrespective staffs.\nThe police has previous! seized a quan\ntiity of explosives and plans and docu\nments belonging to an extensive terrorist\norganization, showing that a plot was\nafoot to bomb the building of the council\nof the empire,\nThe idea of the conspirators was to ob\ntain entr yto the building as newspaper\nreporters and editors. A majority of the\nmembers of the staffs of the two news\npapers convinced the authorities of their\ninnocence of the whole affair and were re\nleased.\nFOWERS IN JURY HAND.\nTold te Conviet for Goebel Murder\nif Plot Be Found.\nHET TINE NI IRIE iH \u00ae3hRr tre\nif Plot Be Found,\nGeorgetown, Ky., Dec, 28. ~The case of\nCaleb Powers, charged with complicity in\nthe murder of William Goebel, will go to\nthe jury Monday. The evidence was com\npleted to-day 2nd the instructions were\nread to the jury.\nThe instructions were about the same as\nthose given the jury at Powers\u2019 last trial,\nfour years ago. They require if it be\nfound that Powers had entered into a\nconspiracy with Youtsey, or any one else,\nto murder Goebel, and Goebel was mur\ndere din accordance with the plot, that\nPowers be found guilty, even though he\nWas not present when the deed was com\nmitted.\nARMY AND NAVY.\nfrom Washington to Fort Terry.\nLieut. Col. ROBERT K. EVANS and Maj. EBEN\nArmy War College.\nCapt. GEORGE G. BAILEY. quartermaster, 1o\nJeffersonville for examination for promotion.\nFirst-class Private HERMAN MANHEIM, Hospital\nCorps, from Fort Moultrie to Fort Douglas.\nReeruit FRANK JESSOP, infantry, Fort Douglas,\ntransferred to Hospital Corps as private, to gen\neral hospital Presidio of San Francisco, for duty\nwith Company B, Hospital Corps,\nSergt. HOMER MENDENHALL, Battery B, First\nField Artillecy, Mounted Service School, Fort\nRiley, transferred as private to Eighth Cavalry.\nRecruits FRANK XN. DELANEY and JAMES\nMOORE \u201cinfantry, recruit depot, Jefferson Bar\nracks, transferred to Hospital Corps as private\nto general hospital, Presidio of San Francisco,\nfor duty with Company B. Hospital Corps.\nMaj. WILLIAM A MERCER. Jlevemth Cavalry,\nfrom Indian Industrial School, Carlisle, Feb\nmary 1, to his regiment.\nCapt. TRA A. SHIMER, assistant smgeon. to\nArny Medical Museum, Washington, esamina\ntion for promotion.\nSergt. FRANK S. PURKEY, Hospital Corps, from\nFort Totten to Fort p\nRecruit ROY A. SHERER. infantry, Fort Sam\nHouston, transferred to Signal Corps as private,\nto Fort Omaha.\nRecruit GEORGE WwW. TAYLOR, Coast Artillery\nCorps, Fort Sam Houston, transferred to Signal\nCorps as private, to Fort Omaha.\nPrivate ALEXANDER J. RICE. Twelfth Recruit\nCompany, \u2018recruit depot, Columbus Barracks,\ntrapsferrcd to Signal Corps, to Fort Omaha\nFollowing enlisted men, Coast Artillery Corps, from\nrecrui. depot, Fort Slocum. \u00abo proper stations:\nPrivate JAMES H. O'CONNELL, Eighteenth\nCompany, to Fort Schuvler: Private THOMAS\nPAYNE, 10st Company. to Fort Totten.\nFollowing enlisted men. Coast Artillery Corps. to\nnated: Private CHARLES W. ROBERTSON,\nEighteenth Company, Fort Schuyler: Private\ntHARLES P. NOWLAND, Mist Company. Fort\nOtten.\nFirst Lieut. LEARTUS J. OWEN, assistant sar\ngeon, to Columbus Barracks.\nRecruits JACK SINGER and THEODORE\nNAZAREK, infantry, recruit depot, Fort Sio\ncum, transferred to Hospitai Corps as privates,\nSeventeenth Infantry, Fort McPherson, trans\nferred as private to band of that regiment, to\nFort Monroe, thence to Havana.\nCapt. 6G. B. RANSOM, Commanders W. B.\nFLETCHER, and J. LUBY, commissioned.\nPassed Assistant Swigeon R. H. MICHELS, de\ntached recruiting station City.\nAssistant Surgeon P. T. DESSEZ, detached Naral\nHospital, Beston, to navy recruiting statiom,\nKansas City.\nNaval Coustructor W. G. DUBOSE, detached naval\nstation, Cavite, February 15, to temporary duty\nBureau of Construction and Repair.\nyard, League Island, to duty head Department\nof Construction end Repair, naval stations, (a\nvite and Olongapo.\nNavale Constructor J. W, WOODRUFF, detached\navy yard, Boston, to naval station, New Or\nleans.\nChief Gunner B. P. MIDDLETON, commissioned.\nGunner D. M. CARRUTHERS. from Sag Harbor,\nto duty in connection with fitting out Montgom.\nery and drty on board when commissioned.\nGunner A. 8S. PEARSON, detached Naval Training\nStation, Newport, to duty connection with fitting\nout Montgomery and duty on board when com\nmissioned.\nPay Director C. W. ABBOT, retired, died at War\nren. December\nMOVEMENTS OF VESSELS\u2014The following move\nments of vessels have beem reported to the\nBureau of Navigation:\nSailed\u2014December 27, Yavkton and Panther. from\nLOAN COMPANIES.\nMONEY TO LOAN\nON PIANOS AND FURNITURE.\nOur rates are 3% per month. Payments, any siz2 1\nsui! your convenience. Nothing fo pay back for\ntwo months afler you get the loan.\nWE PAY OFF HIGH-RATE COMPANIES.\nCITIZENS \"S:us7\u201d CO.\n403 COMMERCIAL BANK BUILDING, NORTHWEST COR. 14th AND STS.\nthey repeat\n\nTAKE ELEVATOR TO FOURTH FLOOR.\nb\nArmy Orders.\nNavy Orders\nWANT LIGHT ON BANKS\nMembers of Congress Will Seek to\nKnow About Failures.\nVarious Bills Provide for Divers\nMethods of Receivership and\nOther Matters,\nThere are symptoms in Congress of a\ngeneral inquiry Into the laws relating to\nnational banks and as to the manner of\nadministering to failed banks through the\nComptroller's office.\nA number of bills have already been\nintroduced in both the Senate and House\nto revise these laws, Senator Burkett, of\nNebraska, has proposed a measure to\nforfeit the charters of national Hanks for\nthe unlawful acts of any officer of such\nbanks that were known to the directors\nof the institution. He has also\nto make the directors of failed re\n*ponsible from their individual estates\nfor all loses sustained by creditors of\nthe failed institutions.\nThere is an effort to revive the oid\nhill proposed In September, 1883, by Wil\nlam J. Bryan to guarantee depositors in\n\u2018national banks against loss by creating a\nsinking fund through a tax of one-quarter\nof 1 per cent on the average daily deposits\nof each national bank for the last quar\nter of the calendar year last passed, the\nfund to be limited to $10,000.000, after\nwhich the tax is to be suspended and\ngreenbacks are to issue against the fund\nto the full amount of it, to prevent a\ncontraction of the currency.\nSenator Smith, of Michigan, has a bill\nto change the manner of paying bank ex\naminers, from the fee system now in\nVogue to a salary basis allowing a flat\nsalary of $4,000 a year. In addition to\nthe changes to be proposed in the law,\nthere is a prospect that after the holidays\nresolutions of inquiry will be offered in\nboth the Senate and House to obtain in.\nformation into the conduct of the re\nceiverships of failed banks since 1883, the\n\u00a5ear of so many bank failures.\nOne Senator has a resclution calling for\na list of such bank receivership, the\namount paid for attorneys and receiver\nShip fees, and the amounts paid to share\nholders and creditors.\nA list of names of recewers, special em\nployes, and attorneys is called for, to\ngether with the amounts paid each. This\nesolution will be offered, its author says,\nvith a view of getting information upon\nwhich bills may be drawn changing the\nmanner of paying receivers and attorneys.\nGATHERED HERE AND THERE\nDr. Oswald Falls, a well-known Egyptologist\nexcavator, has embraced Islam While\nthe N\nThe number of wholesale establishments engged\nin sanghtering and meat packing in the United\nStates during the calendar rear 190% was 923. and\ntheir combined capital was $237,714.63. They fur\n nished employment to TH M5 wage earners, paid\nSUIB HT in wages, consumed materials costing\n$905,856.99. and manufactured products to the value\nof $913 614.624\nIn a collection of Egyptian papyri Prof. Jules\nNicole is reported to have found among some Greek\ntexts an ancient Latin guide thromgh Rome. As it\ncontains an inventory of sculpture and indicates\nthe locality where each piece was located. as well\n\u20188s describes each, it may prove of importance in\nsupplying us with data fer the attribution of as yet\nnameless statues.\nInterest\nJr principal will de due on loans made by this\ncompany during December until\nTWO MONTHS\